comment_data.body: @arttobe thanks for the report. Potentially the daemon searching for devices is having a problem. Can you enable verbose logging (Settings > Languages & Frameworks > Flutter > General) and send us your logs after this happens? (Logs can be found by going to Help > show log in explorer > idea.log).

Without additional information we're unfortunately not sure how to resolve this issue. We're going to close this bug for now, but please don't hesitate to comment on the bug if you have any more information for us; we're happy to reopen. Thanks for your contribution!
What do you need exactly from the log ? Or can I send you the whole?
@arttobe yes, go ahead and attach your entire log. Make sure verbose logging is turned on first. Thanks!

[idea.log](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/files/6027533/idea.log)
Here is my log file

Thank you for your help

I don't see any errors, but it is odd that only Chrome was returned from the daemon. 

Here's something else you can try:
1. On the command line, run `flutter daemon`. This should print out something like:
```
[{"event":"daemon.connected","params":{"version":"0.6.0","pid":60943}}]
[{"event":"daemon.logMessage","params":{"level":"status","message":"Starting device daemon..."}}]
```
and the process will wait for input
2. Type `[{"id":1,"method":"device.enable"}]` After a bit, you should see lines like:
```
[{"id":1}]
[{"event":"device.added","params":{"id":"chrome","name":"Chrome","platform":"web-javascript","emulator":false,"category":"web","platformType":"web","ephemeral":false,"emulatorId":null}}]
[{"event":"device.added","params":{"id":"287E1F39-AE03-44BD-ACDB-7F668B1E32EA","name":"iPhone SE (2nd generation)","platform":"ios","emulator":true,"category":"mobile","platformType":"ios","ephemeral":true,"emulatorId":"apple_ios_simulator"}}]
```

From your logs, only Chrome was returned as a device, but I wonder if you get a different result in your terminal. If you continue to get only Chrome in your terminal, then I think there may be an issue in flutter that causes `flutter devices` to return different results than `flutter daemon`.

Another thing you could try is adding an Android emulator (I think you have a real device connected?) and seeing if this shows up in IntelliJ.

At the moment flutter runs just fine over the command line on my android phone (galaxy s10 lite android 11)

Tomorrow I can add an Simulator and send you the results. do you has any other ideas?

I get my phone over the commandline 
Like in the picture at top oft this issue

@arttobe so to be clear, I know you were already getting multiple devices using `flutter devices`, but I want to check that you can also get multiple devices using `flutter daemon` as I described above.
Ah sorry I had a long day I will check it tomorrow. Thank you for your help

This is my output from flutter deamon an it looks like that my Phone is there

[{"event":"daemon.connected","params":{"version":"0.6.0","pid":326520}}]
[{"event":"daemon.logMessage","params":{"level":"status","message":"Starting device daemon..."}}]
[{"id":1,"method":"device.enable"}]
[{"id":1}]
[{"event":"device.added","params":{"id":"chrome","name":"Chrome","platform":"web-javascript","emulator":false,"category":"web","platformType":"web","ephemeral":false,"emulatorId":null}}]
[{"event":"device.added","params":{"id":"RF8N21RBH9K","name":"SM G770F","platform":"android-arm64","emulator":false,"category":"mobile","platformType":"android","ephemeral":true,"emulatorId":null}}]
I have also added a Emulator, but it also not works.

@arttobe really strange! I'm not sure what could cause this discrepancy between calling `flutter daemon` on the command line and within the plugin. It looks like from your IDE logs that the same command is being used. Sorry this is not apparent.

One more thing you could try is disabling web by calling on command line: `flutter config --no-enable-web` (you can later reverse this with `flutter config --enable-web`. This should remove Chrome from your list of devices (e.g. if you try `flutter devices`). Then you can restart your IDE and get logs the same way as before. I'm suggesting this in case there's a problem with the plugin processing multiple devices or if somehow the environment is different within the plugin.

I have tried this and the result is the same. I also tried AndroidStudio but is the same result. I also tried to run it as root and alos the same result

Do you has any further ideas

We're thinking there may be potential race conditions with daemon startup. You could try killing all of the running daemons and see if you get the correct devices when the IDE restarts them.

You can find the processes to kill with this on the command line: `ps xa | grep flutter | grep daemon | grep -v java`
It is still not working anymore advices
